Yes! ESP32 can send Telegram messages perfectly. It has WiFi built-in, so you can make HTTPS requests to Telegram's API.

**Simple example:**

```cpp
#include <WiFi.h>
#include <HTTPClient.h>

const char* ssid = "your-wifi";
const char* password = "your-password";
String botToken = "your-bot-token";
String chatID = "your-chat-id";

void sendTelegram(String message) {
  HTTPClient http;
  String url = "https://api.telegram.org/bot" + botToken + "/sendMessage?chat_id=" + chatID + "&text=" + message;
  http.begin(url);
  http.GET();
  http.end();
}

void setup() {
  WiFi.begin(ssid, password);
  while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED) delay(500);
  
  sendTelegram("ESP32 is online!");
}
```

Use the **UniversalTelegramBot** library for cleaner code. You can send messages on events (button press, sensor readings, etc.) or on a timer - no cloud server needed!

For receiving messages, the ESP32 can use long polling since it's always powered on (unlike GitHub Actions).
